\par\plain \f1\fs24\b1\i0\ul\ulc0
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\sa240\sb240\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f1\fs24\b1\i0	\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f1\fs24\b1\i0 What does literary fantasising, this particular mental faculty, lie in opposition to, in Wolf\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s eyes?}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f1\fs24\b1\i0	\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f1\fs24\b1\i0 It is everything that relates to the human ability to create \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8216\'91illusion\u8217\'92 (I.e. to create mental simulations) }{\f2\fs24\b1\i1 outside of the purely artistic.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 A very, very large topic, covering one of the most important, distinguishing and widespread human faculties, of which aesthetic illusion is just one subset, distinguished by the need for a }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93inciting representation\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 ; in distinction to this is what Wolf somewhat dismisses as }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93delusions\u8221\'94, \u8220\'93conceptual and perceptual errors\u8221\'94, \u8220\'93hallucinations\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 and }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93dreams\u8221\'94. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 While art is very interested in these things as subjects }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf3 (examples from art?),}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  the role of such things in art are often set aside. Such things are more the purview of}{\f3\fs24\b0\i1\cf1  }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 psychological, psychoanalytical and neuroscientific literature.}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 However, there is, I hope to show here, much crossover; much of what we could consider \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93non-literary\u8221\'94 mental simulation can have inciting representations, often deliberate (advertising, for example), but often accidental and unformalised. Often, we might argue, what distinguishes it is the  }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 direct }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93phenomenology of our experiences\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  (Walton), rather than being parsed through a text. Not always, however. Can be within its own magic circle, can be participatory with which Huizinga called }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93the play attitude\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 , but often is forced upon us, or seems real: not defined by the }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93ambivalence\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  or deliberate participation which is, according to Wolf, part of the aesthetic illusion. Can often be part of the warp and weft of our lives, more deeply embedded, or afforded less sacred significance and space, than art itself.}
\par\pard\plain \fi720\ltrch\loch \f3\fs24\b0\i1
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls2\ilvl0{\listtext\f3\fs24\b0\i1	\loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93Make-believe and imagining are pervasive in human experience, by no means confined to our interactions with works of fiction\u8230\'85 fiction [is] continuous with the rest of life.\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 (Walton, S&S). }
\par\pard\plain \fi720\ltrch\loch \f3\fs24\b0\i1\cf1
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls2\ilvl0{\listtext\f3\fs24\b0\i1\cf1	\loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f3\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 "The mental cinema is always at work in each one of us... [it never] stop[s] projecting images before our mind's eye." }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 (Calvino)}{\f3\fs24\b0\i1\cf1  }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf2 The mind\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s }
