\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf4 EMPATHY!}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\sa240\sb240\ltrch\loch \ls6\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 A big subject of debate amongst reader-response theorists and psychologists.}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\sa240\sb240\ltrch\loch \ls5\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Taking the view of another. Chris Allen Thomas - }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93empathy is the ability of people to recognise and respond to the emotions of others\u8221\'94. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 M.H. Davis - empathy is the }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93reactions of one individual to the observed experiences of another.\u8221\'94 - \u8220\'93}{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 simulates what is going on in another person\loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8217\'92s mind\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 (Feagin).}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\sa240\sb240\ltrch\loch \ls5\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Different from sympathy, which is the emotional response to the emotional experiences of another }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 as other}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 , as opposed to empathy, which involves a degree of perspective-taking; of understanding not just the situation externally, but the mental situation internally. Relates to German term }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 Einfuhlung }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 (\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94feeling into\u8221\'94). Dunn (1988) states that maybe it is difficult to separate these two states.}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\sa240\sb240\ltrch\loch \ls5\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 (Margaret Morris) Either cognitive Empathy - deliberate \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93perspective taking\u8221\'94, or emotional empathy, which is mostly-unconscious sharing of emotions due to emotional contagion. }
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\sa240\sb240\ltrch\loch \ls5\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Relies entirely on the ability to simulate the minds of the other, a }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93theory of mind\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 or what Alison Lee calls }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93mentalising\u8221\'94.}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  and can produce very strong emotional responses (similar to emotion in fiction, though actually based on reality?). Part of what Davies & Stone call }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93}{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 folk psychological\~practice\loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8221\'94, \u8220\'93a practice in which we all engage on an everyday basis.\u8221\'94}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\sa240\sb240\ltrch\loch \ls5\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Required because of the hard problem of consciousness, the inaccessibility of other minds}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf3  (citation?)}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  - tied to qualia (introduced by CI Lewis in 1929) - \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93}{\f3\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb2\highlight2 the subjective or qualitative properties of experiences.\loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb2\highlight2 (Kind), including \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93}{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 perceptual experiences, bodily sensations, felt reactions and emotions and felt moods\loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb2\highlight2  . These are very difficult to study, and their existence has caused }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb2\highlight2 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93considerable controversy in philosophy of mind\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb2\highlight2  (Kind).}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\sa240\sb240\ltrch\loch \ls5\ilvl0{\listtext\f1\fs24\b1\i0	\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f1\fs24\b1\i0 BIOLOGICAL BASIS }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 - Kohler (infants gain self-objectification and empathy at 2); Farrow et. Al (2001) and Oschner et. Al (2004) found the precuneus and prefrontal cortex and left superior frontal gyrus as important for empathy.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Vogeley & Fink (2003) - Precuneus (in the brain) is associated with the taking of perspectives, both first-person and spatial third-person, with differental activation in the bilateral precuneus when first-person (because of agency?), though Alison Lee is not sure whether this is the source of mental imagery, or the mechanism by which we understand the perspectives of others.}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\sa240\sb240\ltrch\loch \ls5\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Very, very important to human society. }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb2\highlight2 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93The importance of empathy is indisputable because it plays a vital role in human social behavior as well as in the behavior of some non-human species\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb2\highlight2 (Rodrigues et al.) }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Frans de Vaal - a}{\f3\fs24\b0\i1  \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93mammalian characteristic\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  -> communicate at an emotional level with our pets. Emotional empathy in voles. Goes against the idea that everything is based on selfish motives in the animal kingdom (in his book Empathy: Its Ultimate & Proximal Bases), and opens up intriguing debates on theory of mind in animals. Some see it, however as HIS autocosmics.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Humphrey and Crook - social animals need cues. }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 -\loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8221\'94probably has an innate basis\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  - }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93we are designed by natural selection to assume that other people have similar mental experiences to ourselves\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 . So, social interdependence leads to the need for simulation.}
